cs.NI, cs.CR, cs.SE, cs.DC, cs.PL 

Reasoning: 
- cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) is the most likely category as the paper proposes an extension to the QUIC protocol to improve its performance during the initial handshake. 
- cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) is also likely as the paper discusses the security aspects of the proposed out-of-band validation token. 
- cs.SE (Software Engineering) is relevant as the paper proposes a new mechanism for distributing the validation tokens. 
- cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) is relevant as the proposed mechanism involves distributed entities such as DNS resolvers. 
- cs.PL (Programming Languages) is less likely but still possible as the paper proposes a modification to the QUIC protocol.
